Note that this setup includes, also in flat space-time, the possibility of a moving detecting surface, as opposed to the resting detecting surface (of the form $[0,\infty)\times {\partial {\Omega}}$ in some Lorentz frame) considered in Section~\ref{sec:ruleflat}. This possibility can be thought of either as moving detectors or as detectors that get switched on at a certain time; the latter scenario makes it clear that the detecting surface can very well have spacelike regions. The detecting surface ${\tilde{\partial} S}$ can be subdivided into the region ${\partial_{\mathrm{ti}} S}$ where it is timelike, the region ${\partial_{\mathrm{psp}} S}$ where it is spacelike or null and lies in the past of $S$, and the region ${\partial_{\mathrm{fsp}} S}$ where it is spacelike or null and lies in the future of $S$; see Firgure~\ref{fig:dS}. The particle may be detected in ${\partial_{\mathrm{ti}} S}$ or ${\partial_{\mathrm{fsp}} S}$, but it cannot reach ${\partial_{\mathrm{psp}} S}$ along a timelike curve from its starting region $\Sigma_0\cap \partial S$. (There may be parts of ${\partial_{\mathrm{ti}} S}$ and ${\partial_{\mathrm{fsp}} S}$ that cannot be reached either.)

